messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

I found three endpoints defined by routes/clients.js, each mounted under the /clients prefix from index.js (app.use('/clients', clientRoutes)). For each endpoint I list the full path and whether each HTTP method is accepted based only on the explicit route handlers in the code.

1) Path: /clients
- all HTTP methods acceptable: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Why: index.js mounts the router at app.use('/clients', clientRoutes). In routes/clients.js there are explicit handlers router.get('/', getClients) and router.post('/', createClient), so /clients accepts GET and POST only. I did not mark HEAD or OPTIONS as accepted because they are not explicitly registered in the source code you provided.

2) Path: /clients/user
- all HTTP methods acceptable: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Why: routes/clients.js contains router.get('/user', getClientsByUser), so the full path is /clients/user and only GET is explicitly registered.

3) Path: /clients/{id}
- all HTTP methods acceptable: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: false
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: true

Why: routes/clients.js contains router.patch('/:id', updateClient) and router.delete('/:id', deleteClient). When combined with the /clients mount path, the parameterized route becomes /clients/{id} (id shown in curly braces per your requirement). Only PATCH and DELETE are explicitly registered.

Notes on interpretation
- I only considered methods explicitly registered in the code (router.get, router.post, router.patch, router.delete). I did not assume implicit behavior from Express (for example, automatic HEAD responses for GET or CORS/OPTIONS handling) because you requested determination based on the code, not experiential assumptions.
- Path parameters are presented as {id} to match your required OpenAPI-style syntax.
